    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. one more thing, we're also concerned about the durability of the surface. in some of these high-density sections, the interlacing is so tight that it's almost non-porous. from a quality control standpoint, does that level of density actually make the fabric more resistant to external contaminants or environmental degradation, or does it just make the material more brittle?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A non-porous, ultra-dense weave can indeed offer some resistance to superficial contaminants, like dust or light moisture, because there are fewer pathways for them to penetrate the structure. However, this comes at a cost, as it often makes the fabric significantly more brittle.\n\nWhen the interlacing is too tight, the material loses its ability to flex or absorb minor stresses, which increases its susceptibility to tearing or breaking under repeated stress. The structural integrity shifts from being resilient to being rigid. From a quality control perspective, you need to balance that density against the material's tensile strength and elasticity.",
      "source": "target",
